<DOC><DOCNO> AP890809-0050 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0617EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     08-09 0547</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0563</SECOND><HEAD>Chilly Winds Send Shivers Over the East</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A brisk batch of cool air swept across the eastern half of thenation today, breaking record low temperatures from New England toTexas.   In Las Vegas, fierce winds registering at 99 mph overturnedprivate airplanes at McCarran International Airport, and anaccompanying storm caused power outages and minor flooding lateTuesday.   The cool air was ushered in by a large high pressure system,dropping early morning temperatures into the 50s and 60s across theeastern half of the nation, and into the 40s over the northern andcentral Appalachians.   Record low temperatures were set in Chattanooga, Tenn., with areading of 57 degrees; in Hartford, Conn., with a reading of 50degress; in Houston with 66 degrees; in Mobile, Ala., with 63degrees; in San Angelo, Texas, with 60 degrees; and in Youngstown,Ohio, with 44 degrees.   Temperatures were warmer across the Gulf Coast and the westernthird of the nation.   Florida was hit by scattered showers this morning, withthunderstorms over the coastal waters of the south Atlantic andGulf Coast states.   Earlier Tuesday evening, a thunderstorm in northeast Florida,near the Putnam and Volusia County line, produced 1-inch hail andwind gusts over 60 miles an hour. Lightning set a house on fire inPutnam County.   The severe thunderstorm struck Las Vegas with wind gusts to 99miles an hour Tuesday night, turning over 80 airplanes at the SkyHarbor and McCarran airports. No injuries were reported.   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstormsfrom the Carolinas to Florida and the eastern half of the GulfCoast; showers and thunderstorms in the afternoon and eveningacross the intermountain region and the northern and centralRockies, and most numerous over the Great Basin area.   Temperatures were forecast to be in the 70s from the Great Lakesand the eastern half of the Ohio Valley across the Appalachians tothe northern and Middle Atlantic Coast; in the 60s or 70s along thePacific Coast; in the 90s over the Florida Peninsula and from thesouthern half of Texas across the southern Plateau to the interiorvalleys of California; above 100 degrees over the Desert Southwest;and in the 80s across the rest of the nation.   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 43 degrees at Bradford,Pa., to 94 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 63 fair; Boston 59 fair; Buffalo 51 fair;Charleston, S.C. 66 cloudy; Cincinnati 55 fair; Cleveland 56 partlycloudy; Detroit 62 cloudy; Miami 78 partly cloudy; New York 62fair; Philadelphia 59 fair; Pittsburgh 49 foggy; Portland, Maine 50fair; Washington, D.C. 58 fair.   _Central: Bismarck 55 fair; Denver 65 fair; Des Moines 57 fair;Fort Worth 64 fair; Indianapolis 54 fair; Kansas City 60 fair;Nashville 58 fair; New Orleans 71 fair; Oklahoma City 63 fair; St.Louis 66 partly cloudy; Minneapolis@St. Paul 60 fair; San Antonio72 partly cloudy.   _West: Albuquerque 68 partly cloudy; Anchorage 58 rain; Boise 73partly cloudy; Honolulu 79 partly cloudy; Las Vegas 82 cloudy; LosAngeles 64 fair; Phoenix 93 fair; Salt Lake City 71 partly cloudy;San Diego 68 cloudy; San Francisco 57 cloudy; Seattle 59 fair.   _Canada: Montreal 55 partly cloudy; Toronto 50 fair.</TEXT></DOC>